description: American Black Bear (Ursus americanus) This is a very rare picture of an American Black bear cub in its den. I was working with a bear biologist for the National Park Service when I found this den. Together we checked the den and put the camera inside just taking pictures when we got the one you see.
Taken by our wildlife camera, very close-up shots of head and body.
Blursus americanus. Damn my shaky hands in low morning light.

Half-awake at night near Beehive Meadow I could hear what sounded like a person walking slowly through the woods (why that didn't alarm and fully wake me up I have no idea).  In the morning there were bear tracks on the soaking wet trail.
On the last leg near the trail from Tuoloumne Meadows to White Wolf

One of our reintroduced cubs pays a visit.

While the bears in Sagehen are wild and we hardly ever see them, sometimes we see our reintroduced cubs in the spring when there is too much snow for them to disperse yet.

Evening in the Crescent Meadow area.

Only one cub.  Saw a different mother/single cub pair farther west along the road, too.
A "trouble bear" tagged by the park service, at Crescent Meadow in Sequoia National Park.
Fresh bear scat. Foot for scale.

Same story as the Mountain lion. This was visitor #2. Not certain if this is U. americanus or U.americanus californienis.  Even though I live in a highly populated area I think I'll get me one of these cameras.

Conversations of bears dominated camp talk throughout the trip, and sure enough less than 10 minutes after chowing down at the Silver City Resort and on our way back to civilization, we spot this momma bear and cub in the middle of the road as we turned the sharp corner heading into the ravine.  It took a few seconds to get the camera ready and by then the two were heading up into the trees.  We pulled ahead and managed to snap a few photos of the pair in there retreat.  Good shot to end the hike.

Brown bear Yosemite Valley June 2015

"The bear that ate the chickens.

"For years I had 3 big hens. Fat, pretty and friendly, the kind that let you pick them up and layed an egg a day. They were in a secure coop ( I thought!) A bear managed to find a weak place where it was wired together and got in and ate them. Nothing but feathers left.........a trail of them going across the field. I had the coop rebuilt using panels of chain link fencing. Someone gave me 7 young chickens and I tried again.  This time he found a small opening near the roof and got in.  I showed up to feed them in the morning and he was in the coop.    I yelled and he climbed back out with a chicken in his mouth. He ran and climbed up the tree and ate that chicken (except for the feet).

"I took the picture while waiting for help to be sure he didn't go back and get the last 2 chickens. He didn't eat any of the feet!  Now the coop has chain link panels across the roof too. That same bear is around often. He has a regular route that he takes to avoid the dogs."

- Tracey Tempel

Observation and photo by Tracey Tempel, sent to nature@nhm.org.

description:
Hiking down Bear Canyon we met up with this huge black bear several times.  He was on and off the same trail as us for about an hour.  Every time we encountered him we would step back with our dogs and let him pass then count to 1,000.  He surprised us again by moving off the trail and taking higher ground. He watched us closely as we maneuvered the dogs and ourselves past him.  This was the largest bear I’ve ever seen, including those in Alaska, and one of those WOW moments. 
Located just a few miles into the mountains above Pasadena, CA.

description:
One of my newer acquaintances... 

Added the full sequence of photos, yet still some work to be done on the sequence.

Watched this Big Guy for over an hour as he grazed on grass and clover in a meadow, took a swim in an alpine lake, and then marked a Sierra Juniper before departing. He was the second bear to visit Bear Lake (personal place name, unlike one on a map) that evening.

At the same time Mule Deer and my friend Lucy, the Wild Turkey, also shared space with him, all at the same time. Have videos of the Big Guy swimming, foraging, marking the tree, and with Lucy and the Mule Deer, and may attach later.

Here's a video of him swimming... https://youtu.be/-XmgfpKT8qI

The first pass to mark the tree then "stomping" his scent in the bear trail... it's mating season...
https://youtu.be/wjF8chzYszs

The second pass to mark the tree with more "stomping"...
https://youtu.be/4Y_BV-4GyOk
 
As on other occasions in other areas, had lived with the bears here for some time... in this case, from April through the summer, into September... Tracking them, observing and interacting with them. 

Once again, the general area is provided, yet avoiding being specific to protect bears and wildlife from hunters.

Beautiful Big Guy hanging out in a secret place in South Lake Tahoe, so the pinpoint location shall remain a secret with a few... bears in urban places need safe and cool places to rest in the summer heat as they struggle to coexist in their homeland that humans now claim as theirs. This was my second visit to this location after taking a tour with a fellow community bear advocate who answers bear calls for at South lake Tahoe.

One of 70 bear sightings (I define each sighting as a bear not seen in the same place that day, or within 2 hours at another location) I had during 2019... Ran across this young male Black Bear on several occasions this past year as it foraged on spring growth and later marked trees during the mating season. Once again the area is correct, yet I avoid pinpointing the location as it would make this bear (and all Black Bears I've seen) vulnerable to bear hunters. Most of the time I'm fortunate get somewhere from 10-120+ okay photos from bear observations, and since I'm leery of entering more than a few bear observations on this site, thought I'd add a few more of this beautiful "masked" young male... a trait seen in several bears of the area.

description: This is a regularly-used black bear trail. Bears use this trail in spring, summer and fall. It has been in use for many years, with bears traveling over it for the past dozen years at least. Each summer, the footsteps get more worn into the ground. Winter tends to restore the appearance of the trail, but it gets plenty of use the rest of the year. I followed this trail up the hill and over the other side. Scat was found along the trail to also confirm black bear as the main user of it. In some of these photos, you can see the regularly-placed footsteps, which the bears use over and over.

tag_list: black bear trail, tracking, stomp trail
description:
Black bear stomp trail that I followed through the forest. The bears had been using this trail for months to get to an area of open field where grass grows tall. The bears regularly feed on these grasses in spring. Every spring, I get trail camera videos of the bears feeding in that field. Over time, they develop these regularly-used trails to and from the feeding area. The steps get worn into the landscape and are easy to follow for long distances. There is a pond, a creek, and  spring along this trail that the bears use for water sources.

Videos:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GMAxALrZEIk

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NktRGwy56ms
last day we got the bear on the animal camera.

Female Black Bear fishing for Kokanee Salmon at Taylor Creek, CA.

October 12, 2018

Kokanee salmon were "accidentally" introduced into Lake Tahoe in the 1940's. It was several years before the black bears began to seek the spawning salmon as a food source. Over many generations, the knowledge of the salmon was passed along to more and more bears, with many learning by watching.

Black bear trail and sign. Stomp trail and a sapling tree beat up and broken off by the bear as part of scent marking activities. Bear fur and scratch marks were on the bark of the Douglas fir sapling. Stomp trail led to and from this tree.
black bear scat composed of vegetation
Well-used stomp trail used by black bears near a field where they were feeding on spring grasses. Repeated use, as well as stomping gait, wear these trails into the landscape.

Black bear trail showing several shrubs bent over as the bear straddle-marked on them. Bears do this along regularly-used trails to leave behind scent. Often, they dribble urine as they straddle the shrubs. This ber trail included well-worn sections of stomp trail, as well as a scat deposit composed of vegetation.

description: The largest male Black Bear I have seen in the park to date. Was about 75 yards out with full zoom on my 300mm telephoto lens to get this capture. This male was one of 5 Black Bears I encountered hiking south towards Buena Vista Lake Saturday, all of them untagged w/ no collar. Just before crossing Illilouette Creek in the Illilouette Basin my hiking partner and I came head on with this male at the junction. After a brief stare down within 50 yards of the bear we continued on forward. The male quickly turned around and began sprinting in the opposite direction leaving a huge trail of dust. An amazing encounter through and through.

description:
What did we find and what happened here?

Was hiking around with a couple friends and came across these remains. There was much speculation as to what happened here.  How did two predators wind up dead in the same place? Are they bears or something else?

First what we have:
1.)	There were 2 pieces of hide (photos 5,7,8) and some other scattered fur bits, originally thought to be from the same animal until we spotted the 2nd jaw.
2.)	There was one scull (photos 3,4,5,10,11,12)
3.)	One complete jaw (photos 1,9) and a second half jaw (photo 2)
4.)	Very few other bones around, though there was one piece of what appeared to be a leg bone with both ends broken off and all the marrow hollowed out (not pictured).
5.)	There were some small piles of what appeared to be fur and small pieces of bone (photo 6) that I am guessing was the stomach contents of the dead animals.

This listing is for the remains. If anyone can come up with a good idea what killed them, I can make a second listing. 
 @beartracker , is this something up your alley? 
Anyone else want to try and solve this deep woods murder mystery?


Our  speculations:
1.)	Two bear cubs climbed a rotten tree snag and it fell over killing them.
2.)	An adult male killed two bear cubs.  I have heard that brown bears will do this so that the mother will be ready to mate again.  Do black bears do it as well?
3.)	Killed by a hunter. Because, at least one of the skins appears to have been pulled off a leg leaving a tube of skin with the fur inside (photos 7 & 8) and other than the skulls, most of the bones were gone. Though, to me, it seems unlikely anyone would want the meat and would leave the skins.  This was also found on a rather steep hillside and not very near any kind of trail.
4.)	They are coyotes, or some other predator.  Because, what we were guessing is the stomach contents appears to be all bones and fur, and bears aren’t really hunters.  We did see quite a bit of bear scat in other areas that showed mostly grass from the meadow.

description:
Here's Mom and her three cubs of the year, seen again about two weeks after the first observation.

Had noticed pine cone/seed/nut foraging by bears in the area, and heard the foraging in the distance for several days. Tracked Mom and her youngsters to this area, and had sat and heard them for about an hour or so... it was beginning to get dark, and hadn't heard the family or another bear in the area for about 15 minutes... so dropped down to an old road to make my way back to camp when I stumbled across them. The youngsters had been climbing the Jeffrey Pine trees and knocking down cones, and Mom had been working the lower branches for cones. Have photos of the pine seed foraging activity in the area and may share later, presumably most from Mom and her youngsters.

description: large bear scat, on diet of Big Berry Manzanita fruit, Los Padres National Forest

A yearling (cubs of the year a bit smaller and shorter in late July) on its own... and a bit on the light side for weight this time of year. Think I caught another glimpse of him in 2020, and was doing okay.

Saw this cub of the year desperately foraging on his/her own and was able to see this youngster couple more times before the snow arrived for the year. Why this little one was on it's own, will never know... did he/she have brothers and sisters, was it's mother killed on the often frantically driven state highway several miles below, or was she killed in the year's bow-hunting season... other possibilities too.

Do know this little one was in a starving situation as the winter season approached. Will post one of the other encounters made about three weeks later. This guy, would follow me around as I tracked other bears in the area, remaining about 25 to 50 meters away on several occasions.

Three weeks after I first met this little one, a cub of the year on its own and struggling to find food. He (thinking he) walked right up to me and continued to stay close to me for a while. 

Shared what may his story on the observation of three weeks earlier, posted recently too.

It's a very, very tough life for a cub of the year on it's own.

description: Black Bear scat?

Fortunate to tag along with folks who work to keep Tahoe Bears safe.

With the exception of the first photo, the photos are in sequence. We were called to look for mom and her youngsters, and I located Mom on the beach side of the home, after noticing her tracks leading into the lake and back out. I then followed the beach access trail to the back yard to see if the family would make their way there... And they did!

Great observation and encounter!... with the cubs playing and their Mom watching over them. Mom also got a good scratch going on a large and very old Jeffrey Pine Tree. Then the beautiful family made their way through the neighborhood, disappearing on their way to a preserved greenway.

Thankfully, there are many bear friendly and Bear Smart people up at the lake. And I'm fortunate to continue to help out with good friends who work hard to keep bears safe and people educated about bears... including the harm their attractants end up doing to bears. Attractants should never be used to get photos or videos of bears or any wildlife... spent part of my career putting an end to wildlife paying the ultimate price after becoming habituated to human attractants: human food, unsecured trash, bird feeders, pet food, smelly items in garages and vehicles, fruit trees, and poorly maintained campsites with exposed food and trash... All this and more leads to the death of bears, including families of bears.

Provided a general location of South Lake Tahoe.

While tagging along with a bear advocate, we visited a place very popular with Big Guys especially in the heat of summer. There are at least five bear beds in this small area concealed by willows and other riparian vegetation... and another Big Guy was in a bear bed only 15' feet away. These bear beds are used repeatedly by several bears as they seek a cool and safe place in South Lake Tahoe, and they share this place... very interesting behavior, often seen by bears in urban areas. Only a few people know about this location in order to protect this refuge for bears.

I have already shared another observation of this beautiful bear seen again on August 9, 2018, when I returned alone to see who was around... shared that observation on January 13, 2020. May also eventually share some bear sign photos seen in this area and other locations in South Lake Tahoe.

Will share the observation of the other Big Guy in a bed about 15 feet away... to follow this observation... If you spend much time around bears, you'll be able to identify each by their often subtle individual characteristics. This is also the same day we saw the beautiful bear family, that observation shared before this one.

The location is a general one and is not a specific indication of where these bears feel safe.

The second Big Guy... seen about 15 feet away from the other Big Guy shared earlier in another observation. In addition to the different growth around the bear beds, you can see that these are two separate bears by looking at them... their faces are distinctly different as well as their bodies and coloration... the time and dates are from the photo data provided with each. I avoid posting additional photos of one observation as separate observations, unless I temporarily forget I had already shared an observation.

Several bear beds are in this area, with an array of bear sign I may share later... a safe haven for the urban bears of South Lake Tahoe, amid all the traffic and tourist activity.

Location is general/generic and avoided sharing any specific information.
I am not sure on this one and would appreciate any feedback. Found at the bottom of a dry creek, mostly composed of Arctostaphylos fruits.

description:
Bear Bed at the base of an old growth Sierra/Western Juniper.

In an open area, a set-up I've found that some large guys tend to use.

Bear Beds have several factors associated with their selection... There's a good all-around view (an elevation gradient is usually the case if present), large tree to escape up (very large for a very large bear) that also serves as general cover from detection and the elements, and what isn't present that you'll find associated with many bear beds, is at least low cover next to the bed leading to/from thicker cover (for bears to safely approach their bed or leave in secrecy if that's a better decision than climbing the associated escape tree).

Oh... had to add an edit that I'm glad a fellow bear person pointed out... one more very important element that's a part of bear bed sites... Bear Scat around the bed. There were several in the immediate area here, and have one in the photos. Thanks @beartracker. 

Very remote location, generalized.

Bear Wallow with trails to and from.

Were several bear tracks in the muddy trails, and included tracks from a mom with two cubs. The water had been stirred up recently... and could tell that the last bear to leave tracks was medium sized. The weather was on an upward very warm trend and activity had become accelerated here in the past week. 

Visit this special place regularly, in remote Bear Country (general location provided), and often see bobcat and coyote tracks here too.

Bear Wallow

Hasn't been used in a couple days, yet plenty of mud on neighboring vegetation (including snapped branches) and downed trees. Claw marks on tree limbs next to wallow, and all tracks seen were two days old or more.

Another special place and area I visit frequently... and see many bears in this immediate area from snow melt to snow fall... and an array of food sources are available from spring through fall in this area. Location remote, and generalized.

Two right front tracks, the one to the right being more recent with a sedge still bent into and part of the tracks, and looking clearer (more definition) and slightly larger. Notice that the track to the left has no vegetation "stuck" in it and it's outline has deteriorated quite a bit. Were other tracks associated with these, yet I only took this photo.

Watched this guy as he heard and smelled another bear in the riparian strip down below him. I missed getting a photo of the other bear, yet was fortunate to watch this guy move into position to make himself known to the other bear. After the other bear left the area, this guy got up and passed behind me. This bear has become familiar with me and has a trait of about half the black bears in this area... a pronounced mask coloration.

Off the beaten path and up the mountain, and near a bear wallow site.

description:
Saw this bear at a place I call Aspen Meadows. A wallow site is located in the riparian vegetation behind this beautiful and wet bear.

The first bear I saw here this day here, and after returning from a bear hike, saw another bear here in the early evening... in both cases, the bears knew I was around, yet have become somewhat familiar with my scent. Sometimes bears may even respond by marking trees right in front of me. 

First photo is slightly out of the earlier part of the sequence... when my presence was detected.

Below is a video that shows this young bear marking a tree, before hiding behind another marking tree... a stunted Sierra/Western Juniper, it's growth impacted by being marked by bears for decades - more detailed observation of this marking tree and "stomping" trail, hopefully soon.

https://youtu.be/rFVUG85t1MU

description:
While sitting on the edge of a meadow complex I call Last Chance Meadows, this young guy came out following my trail and stopping forage briefly. As he continued on my scent trail, he approached then looped around me... disappearing in a thick riparian area that blended into the forest.

Also attached a YouTube video of him circling around me. You may notice that he has lost clumps of hair, and while bears shed, the hair loss looks reminiscent of mange compared to other bears I've seen while shedding fur. You'll also see him drop a scat as his circles about...

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gYK8an6hPt8&t=2s

Once again, chose a general location... actually in a very remote area.

Typical Jeffrey Pine seed/cone foraging of black bears in the Eastern Sierra. This foraging activity is from the Mom and cubs of the year seen in shared observations of July 27 and August 5, 2020.

I had been tracking Mom and her cubs for a couple weeks before the July 27, 2020 observation, and continued into August. They also would forage during the late afternoon and into and through the evenings within a few 100 meters of one of my campsites... and I could hear them while they foraged about for pine seeds in cones of the season... as well as foraging for insects under rocks before transitioning mostly to pine seeds. I was able to learn Mom's movement habits through this section of the Eastern Sierra.

Notice the difference in bear foraging for pine seeds in comparison to what you will find when squirrels forage for pine seeds... squirrel foraging may be cleaner to slightly rough at times, yet they are not unable to tear cones apart like bears do using their front feet and mouths. If you look at the August 5, 2020 observation with Mom and her three cubs of the year, you'll see Mom holding a cone with her paws while going after pine seeds. I also watched them at work as I have other bears... Mom will go up the trees, remaining close to the trunk, tearing cones down that she can reach, as well as mostly lower branches. The cubs climb up the tree, and being lighter and more nimble, will climb out on a limb, and sever cones, so they drop to the ground. Neat stuff!

This is a remote area with an old logging road passing through part of it, and location chosen is generic and then obscured to protect this family and other bears of the area.

"Straddle" Marking Tree on the edge of a mountain meadow, high in the Eastern Sierra.

This trail leads to a fork, and each fork leads to separate Springtime Wallows that are usually dry by summer solstice.

Notice "Stomping" trail closeup photo and closeup of a decent collective clump of bear hair on the"Straddle" Tree.

Location is remote, far from access roads, and I chose a generic town for the general location.

About a day old.

High in the Eastern Sierra, in a very remote location. Near a special place I annually pack light and hike to... and build a basic shelter under an old growth Sierra Juniper using white fir branches.

Markleeville, California chosen as a very general location.

Black Bear insect foraging... large black ants the objective.

About three days old. Notice the size of the large downed tree 9Jeffrey Pine) that was rolled and shifted over... even though it has been decomposing for a while, and the climate is mostly dry in summer, I couldn't budge it at all. Bears have amazing strength! And determination.

Remote location in the Eastern Sierra generalized and obscured.

One of the most atypical Bear Beds I've found over the years...

Usually Bear Beds are situated in a way to provide a view, and placed on a slope or ledge overlooking an area, in this case a mountain meadow providing ample spring and early summer forage, mostly clover and some grass. This area is also a major travel route to a pass over a ridge.  This Bear Bed does provide a good view in all directions in an area where the wind direction tends to vary and swirl around (an advantage, to know who's around in all directions) throughout the day, spring to fall.

Most Bear Beds are placed at the base of a large escape tree... in this case, the escape tree is several feet away... and the Bear Bed site is without cover from behind/upslope to aid in a safe observant approach and a safe route to leave the area if the escape tree is not the best choice to avoid danger and detection.

Another special aspect about this Bear Bed, is the origin of the bed itself... placed in a depression created by a burned out base of a Jeffrey Pine Tree that once stood there before the area burned about five or so years ago.

Notice the collection of bear scat, which is very typical of Bear Bed sites.

Remote location, generalized and obscured.

Saw this guy while assisting a bear friend who volunteers for a bear organization we support up at the lake... we were tracking bears through town and we caught sight of this guy passing through a backyard that serves as a corridor connecting two greenway corridors. One of several bears seen in a day and a half, all depending on humans to coexist with them... in a place that has always been their home.

description:
Been seeing this Big Guy this year, and finally saw him out in the open... foraging on clover and grass at a favorite place I call Bear Lake. He's usually allusive, using bear trails beyond easy view/access. This is also the third year of getting to know his habits, frequent travel routes, trees he marks and gets a good scratch on, and part of his territory.
Took the first photo after he detected my presence after the prevailing wind did a 180 (which usually happens every 10 minutes or so). The last photo in the sequence is actually the first photo... I worked my way down to him to get better photos, as the ole camera is challenged when it comes to zooming in and focusing.

This beautiful bear makes the Eastern Sierra his home and he is a backcountry bear... and it takes tracking, hiking, and persistence balanced with patience to be able to see him. Been fortunate to see other bears this year too... may share more observations as 2021 gets warmer.

Had to add... the third photo shows "Rusty" looking the opposite direction... another bear is up the slope and making a bit of noise. Notice his posture... one I've seen before, indicating his position and stance when it comes to another bear showing up at a popular place.

description:
Sometimes you are drawn to an area... and for the better part of almost two hours, you are in the presence of a youngster foraging in the open... 
In this case, a yearling on his own, as mating season has been the mode for the adults. He may look very small, yet you can get a better idea of his larger size in some of the photos where I had walked off once, letting him know he was safe here. You can also compare his size to the cubs of the year in photos from observations of last year in July and August of bear families.

After this little one detected me when the prevailing wind reversed, he went into cover at the edge of the meadow. I eventually went into cover too, yet found him wandering near me and circling about to get a good dose of my scent and chemical cues... at the same time, I was taking photos of bear trails and tracks, beds, and marking/scratch trees (maybe post later). Then I stepped into the open, checking out plants (observations soon) and bear wallows in the dry lake, along with Wild Turkey sign (may also eventually share these observations), I walked off...

Then I circled back around on another small ridge (photos from a distance - and also show the yearling size better), this youngster came back out into the open. Then I returned to get closer again, and after 1 hour and 50 minutes, he slowly walked up slope and to the NE.

Have several videos along with more photos, and at least one video may eventually be seen on Instagram.

One of my favorite places, I call Bear Lake (not a place name on a map), it is as dry as it usually becomes in late July to early August... The winter was a very dry one here... things are probably the driest I've ever seen going back to 1986... Hope this little one and all the bears do well. Eventually will share plant observations of the area... and the timing of flowers appearing is unlike any I've seen, all the way up to and beyond 8,000'.

Only the first two photos are reversed and out of sequence.

description:
Saw this medium to large sized guy at a place I call Bear Lake. The suns rays had already been obscured by the ridge to the west and my camera has difficulty focusing at  times... approached a bit closer to get better photos. The first photo is out of sequence and the next to last photo should be earlier in the sequence. His coloration is somewhat unique for this area.

He is foraging for the last available clumps of moist clover and grass. The bears here, as in many places I've visited avoid sedges... I've seen other observations of bears on social media saying they eat sedges, yet that may be a local thing, and the species may be different from here. This morning I did find two very interesting bear scats, consisting of something I've never seen in a bear scat anywhere... rushes, thinking a Juncus species. Will share one of these unique scats, along with the evidence of foraging for them soon. It is extremely dry in this area of the Eastern Sierra, the driest I've ever noticed, indicating a very dry winter. The bears are foraging more often than usual, and are actively traveling about more often than seen before too. To add to the challenges of finding food, two large areas, one in the Eastern Sierra, and another in the neighboring Pine Nut Mountains of the Great Basin were scorched by wildfires. Tough year for bears.

Saw two bears about midday yesterday... This is the big guy of the "couple" making his way through the area to wait near a massive bear bed site (will share photos later) in the shade for his companion... a female trailing behind about 100 meters. Once the female arrived, they moved off together. It was difficult getting photos of them traveling together, and I decided it best to not follow them, giving them their privacy.

Will share a few photos of the female next as another observation, and you'll notice that the time stamp on photos of both overlap as I was getting photos of both before they united in the dark shade. I do have a video panning from the big guy to his mate and may add later, and hope to share on Instagram soon.

I dropped down to a favorite mountain town for WiFi and am heading back up for another night and day, maybe I'll see them again.

Here's the female following behind the big guy, originally trailing at about 100 meters. The first photo is out of sequence, the rest in sequence.

In a couple photos you can see her tasting the air with her tongue and getting a good dose of the male with her Vomeronasal Organ. The day before, I had tracked them in the area, seeing both sets of prints in the area, and followed them to a huge bear bed with a smaller bear bed about 15 feet away, and in close proximity to a White Fir Tree they used for marking (photos in a future observation). As I stood next to the marking tree getting close-up photos, I became covered in the big guy's scent and my jacket has now made my Explorer smell like a male bear.

Wasn't able to get up to Bear Country last week...Saw four bears in under 21 hours in three different locations, after arriving Tuesday afternoon... including the huge Big Guy (will share photos of his massive prints as an observation soon) that visited me at my camp site, walking up 15 feet away. Love Bear Country.
A large track on the Sandberg trail. There was a few more that went off trail.
Killed in the night before, but still there when I drove by at 9AM. 400 pounds.

description: A difficult track series on broken ground.

After arriving back at one of my hangouts and accidentally walking up to a Big Guy 15' away earlier in the evening, saw this young adult male foraging about 75 to 100 meters away, mostly for Greenleaf Manzanita berries. The berries have yet to ripen, yet the bears have been eating them for a month... This is the first year in three years that Greenleaf Manzanita berry production was at moderate to high levels. The two preceding years there was little or no production... something I've noticed in mild winters when there is a deep freeze after they flower earlier than usual. This food source has become very important for bears in this very dry year, coupled with the influx if new bears moving from neighboring areas that had large wildland fires last year.

Have somewhat gotten to know this young guy and he as become a little comfortable with my presence... I had made some noticeable noise when I arrived back at the hangout, and was surprised to see him nearby. The light of day was already diminishing a bit and my point and shoot camera was having challenges focusing past 8 - 10X. He continued to hang around into the dark of night.

Notice his coloration, very dark legs and underside, blonde back, and his distinctive "mask". many bears have exhibit dark rings around their eyes, due to less hair in that area combined with that hair being darker. His "mask" is larger than these rings... and his coloration as a whole can be seen in a good percentage of bears in this region.

Couple number two for the four day week in Bear Country...
Saw the female walk up and as I was walking down to a meadow while checking out bear sign and a new set tracks from a very large Big Guy and moderately sized female... from this couple. Got the feeling they were near, yet the wind was changing direction and thought I wouldn't see them... Yet from down wind the female was walking into the area, picked up my scent and walked into a clump of willows, waiting for the the Big Guy of the Mountain. I thought she was alone, then he appeared a few seconds later, also picking up my scent, turned towards the female obscured by the willows, walked a couple steps, then both ran up-slope just a little and stopped. So I waited for a few minutes hoping they'd reappear. They remained above and hidden so I walked out into the open checking out plants along the way, then sat down for a while. 
After about 15 minutes, heard them foraging for insects under downed trees while remaining up-slope. I eventually moved on.

The first photo is the next to last one, and the photo of the female walking behind the willows is the first in the sequence. Decided to combine the two bears as one observation this time around.

One of the largest bear beds I've ever seen, and the female's bed is about 15 feet away. The second and last photos are of the female's bed. Notice the bear trail impressions, the result of frequent travel/use and of the "stomping" that males do to mark the area with their scent.

I included both bear beds and the stomping/bear trail sign as one observation, because it is one site with many parts, one dependant on the other. There is a marking/scratch tree adjacent to the bear bed site, and due to limits on photos per site, hope to share that soon.

I saw two different mating couples here in a four day span. The first couple seen were considerably smaller than the second couple...  The first couple was shared as two separate observations, the second couple with the Big Guy of The Mountain and his companion shared as one observation... unfortunately, the large female was in the process of moving behind some willows before my camera focused properly.

I strongly believe that this bed site belongs to the Big Guy of The Mountain (have been tracking him and seeing him for three years now) and his large female companion.

description:
Hiked to a more remote location and saw this yearling foraging for grass and other plants... Followed her around for an hour and ten minutes. She (saw characteristics of female bears) was on her own and her Mom may have departed to take part in this year's mating season. Watching this youngster forage it was evident her Mom taught her well. 

You can look at some of my other observations of bear families seen in mid and late summer with cubs of the year for a size comparison... She has it tough looking for food this year as all bears of the area are experiencing due to the above average very dry and hot conditions... So she should have a bit more weight to her.

With the exception of the first photo, they are in sequence and went with the best photos out of the bunch. After foraging she bedded down at the base of a large Jeffrey Pine that had burned in a wildfire about 5 or so years ago to clean up. That's where I left her. May add links to a couple videos of her later.

While watching her I stumbled across a Wild Turkey Mom and her chicks and was able to get a few photos of Mom... Who only moved a few feet off in the thick elderberry, Prunus, willows, and other understory beneath the burned trees. May share that observation later. I returned this past week to this location and accidentally walked up on a female Mule Deer in an alpine lake (maybe share later) and that's where I experienced a strong earthquake... on the edge of on island of live trees and burned trees... Luckily, it was very windy that day, heard a burned tree fall and watched a large branch fall down from another tree 50 to 75 meters away... and had chosen a safe spot up a slope to observe the alpine lake... About 30 minutes later the earthquake hit, rumbling for over a minute. I watched the live and burned trees shake and sway, some branches falling 50' from the trees, and watched and heard many burned trees fall. The aftershocks continued into the next day. Hiking out of there was interesting, as I was surrounded by miles of the old burned area. Be safe out there and enjoy Nature!

description:
First saw this dark yearling on July 2, 2021 and watched her for an hour and 10 minutes...  then during the early evening of July 12, 2021 heard her foraging for insects near a favorite hangout. I walked towards the sounds of a bear foraging for insects under downed trees/logs and rocks and saw her doing her thing. Was fortunate to follow her around while talking to her, and acting like I was foraging also... worked out pretty good.

The next day, saw another yearling foraging about, and he was a multicolored black bear. Throughout the day into the evening I followed both around several times as they foraged alone, one appearing when the other disappeared. Quite an experience...

That second evening I dropped down out of the immediate area to give them a break from me...
The next day, July 16 at 3 PM a change was in the air. For more info please see the observation of the Mule Deer Buck shared just before this observation. I barely made it down the road later that third evening, flames moving close to the road...

Wonder how she is doing?... and the other yearling, and other bears, and all wildlife? This area was impacted by the Tamarack Fire things are different now.

May add a link to a video of her foraging on Instagram. More observations of her from the next day, and of other bears on the way.

First photo out of sequence, rest in sequence.

Second yearling in a couple days that I was able to follow around while he foraged. He eventually become accustomed to me like the dark female the night before... followed both around separately throughout the day. More observations during the same day forthcoming. Forgot my SD card was getting full during this observation, first photo out of sequence... may add phone camera photos/video to this observation later.

Thirty-six hours later, doubt these two yearlings were foraging here, as flames were arriving in the area from the Tamarack Fire and I had to abruptly depart. Hope they are okay and safe.

Knew they were in the area, was tracking them (may share some fresh bear sign in the future) after I heard them in the distance. I peacefully departed and hope to see them again.

Will soon post a video of them playing on Instagram, as well other videos of these two bears enjoying themselves in the Tahoe Basin.

description:
Here's the bear sign left by the two black bears of the previous observation of July 24, 2021 in the Tahoe Basin, as I was tracking and hearing them moving just ahead of me. The photos are in sequence as I followed them along the edge of a meadow. The last photo was taken 8 minutes before I saw the black one, think a female, first appear across the narrow finger of a larger meadow... the brown guy, think a male then appeared shortly after.

I have combined all these as one observation... what you see when tracking bears and to reduce the load on the iNaturalist system.. The Lodgepole pine Marking/Scratch Tree has trails associated with it, and right before I took the first photo, I heard the bears breathing hard and playing, and at one time was closer than I thought, as they played and walked about... you can see the patches of sedge and grasses where they were playing and the fresh trails in the sedge and grasses that they left behind. There is one young Lodgepole Pine Straddling Tree, with a closeup of the bear hair on it, and photos of a wild rose (which species?) also used for straddling to leave a scent (one photo is blurred with the broken branch, yet also included it).

I went back the next evening evening to take photos of the sign they left while I was talking photos of them and will share that as the next observation.

Location is very general and obscured.

Bear sign a day old from where I was watching the two bears play and forage the night before while taking photos of them. Trails and playing areas exactly where I had watched them.

Another Tahoe Basin observation of two other bears seen the next night at a different location on the way, and will catch up on the observations of the two yearlings foraging in an area that was burned by the Tamarack Fire... saw one two days before this area was burned and already shared that observation, and saw both separately the next day several times, one observation already shared.

Locations always generalized and obscured.

Old Bear trail up a Lodgepole Pine.

Here's Brawny, a young male black bear of the Eastern Sierra... we have crossed paths here and there.

I was making my way back to a hangout when I heard a bear foraging for insects nearby, then a few moments later saw Brawny eating Greenleaf Manzanita Berries. I was downwind and blending in, so he decided to check me out and walk up to me... 8 feet away. I said "How you doing Buddy?", and he ran off about 50 meters and stopped. I continued on.

Enjoyed this observation of Brawny as the light of day was fading... about nine or ten days later the Tamarack Fire burned this area... his Home, and the home of other bears.
Wonder how he is doing?

Here's a video of him walking up to me https://youtu.be/kWSB7nLW0Go

Location generalized and obscured.

First saw this yearling the evening before, shared the observation a few days ago. Then after watching a following a multicolored yearling an hour before, she reappeared foraging for insects in downed trees and logs, and under rocks. I think she hears the other yearling nearby and is looking that way in some of the photos. I followed her for a bit and then she moved on... reappearing later several times and was able to get decent photos on one of those occasions... the other times I just watched her from a distance.

These photos were taken the day before the Tamarack Fire blew up due to high winds and very dry conditions... I had dropped partway down the mountain later that evening to give the little bears some space... The next day the fire which was several miles away, intensified and I watched the smoke for a few hours, and wondering why it took three hours before a large retardant dropping plane flew over... a little after 7 pm I saw the flames crossing the ridge heading to this area and barely got out in time... wonder if these little guys and all the bears made it to safety. Much more to wonder about...

Round two of this multicolored yearling about an hour after the first observation of following him around (shared earlier, may add more photos to that observation) and nine minutes after the black yearling passed by (previous observation). Saw them several times throughout the day.

The Tamarack Fire burned into this area the next evening and into the following day...

May add links to foraging videos for both of these little ones.

Last night, I was out on another bear walk while up at the lake and heard bears foraging... made my way over to the commotion and saw the larger bear, I believe to be Mom, first, and she kept looking over to the smaller bear, who was more leery as he moved about... he was larger than a yearling, and much smaller than an adult, yet was acting like mom was in charge of where to go and when. They foraged throughout the area, stopping a few times to play along the way. Eventually they made their way down to a hiking/strolling trail, crossing it while foraging and I decided to move on.

Conditions were challenging taking photos due to the smoke in the area and the clouds remaining after the thunderstorm and rain... followed them from 7:19 pm to 8:09 pm.

First photo out of sequence, rest in sequence.

May be adding links to some videos some.

description: GPS = 4" x 2"

Scat pile, composed entirely of berries and fruits. It appears to be made up of a meal eaten upslope a ways. Many fruits of *Arctostaphylos glandulosa* present, which is a plant species exceedingly uncommon until you get a good ways upslope from from this spot. I collected some of the manzanita fruits for scattering around while I hike. God speed, hopeful future manzanitas. Some *Prunus ilicifolia* stones also present, which can be found at pretty similar elevations to the site of observation. Coin used for scale is a US quarter dollar (¢25 piece), 24.26 mm, 0.955 inch in diameter. 

Later note: The manzanita fruits here appear to be those of *Arctostaphylos glandulosa* subsp. *gabrielensis*, based on the fused nutlets, forming "stones". Generally you only find that subspecies in the "interior" reaches of the San Gabriels. Makes me wonder how far from the source these berries were carried by the bear. Alternatively, I will have to check out the *A. glandulosa* on Sunset Ridge to the north. There may be very non-interior population of *A. glandulosa* subsp. *gabrielensis* up there.
place_guess: Marshall Canyon Regional Park, La Verne, CA, US

description: Pile of scatted fruits, in one of the upper canyons of Marshall Canyon, San Gabriel Mountains. Scat mostly those of *Arctostaphylos glauca*, which makes me question the intelligence of this animal. There is *no* nutrition to be gleaned from those berries. They are just a dry skin wrapped around a woody indigestible stone. There are no *Arctostaphylos glauca*, that I know of, this low in Marshall Canyon, so they were likely foraged higher up and pooped out lower down. Also, the scat was at the opening of a canyon that leads up into the mountain slope proper, so the animal was likely walking downslope, out of that canyon. Coin used for scale is a US quarter dollar (¢25 piece), 24.26 mm, 0.955 inch in diameter.

While working as part of the search team for Tamarack the Cub (who escaped a wildlife rescue and care center after he was rescued from the Tamarack Fire), two friends and I noticed a Mom and two of her cubs staying cool in the shade of the Tahoe Forest.

Location was generalized and obscured.

Tamarack the Cub feeling safe in a Jeffrey Pine after another member of the search team stumbled across him. It was a very smokey day, resulting in challenging photo conditions.

All the members of the search team met up and Cal Fish and Game made a determination that Tamarack was okay. He has escaped a wildlife rescue and care center and was out and about for several days and many people were concerned about him, since he was healing from burns on his paws and was recovering from a severe lack of food. We all hope he is doing well... The Caldor Fire burned into the nearby area a couple weeks later. Hope bears and other wildlife impacted by both the Caldor and Tamarack Fires are okay, yet there's no doubt many animals, especially the small ones could not escape the fast moving flames.

About a week or so before being here with Tamarack, I assisted with the rescue of Tamarack's brother, Raymond who actually was rescued by people working in the Markleeville area... A large group helped get Raymond into a transport enclosure and many thanks to all involved. One guy in particular was the one who made the big difference when Raymond, burned and very hungry, walked up to him while he and others were working on a construction project. Efforts by fire crews, private land managers, construction workers, and Carol from the Bear League came together to help Raymond. The construction guys wished Raymond was named Burt - important side note. Similar efforts were there to help rescue Tamarack and search for him later.

Location generalized and then obscured.

Been responding to some bear calls for the Bear League at Lake Tahoe and got to this location after a deputy had arrived.

Mom and one cub were outside the home, while two cubs were inside. The owners of the home were away. I managed to get Mom to call the 2 cubs out of the home while standing up to Mom during the four times she charged at me... Mom eventually realized I wasn't leaving so she called the cubs out. They all moved on and I placed a bear mat at the broken window. Relatives of the homeowners arrived, all was well and another Bear League member brought over a larger bear mat.

If you live in bear country, secure your attractants and do not feed bears as you are egging them on into trouble which could lead to their death... And encourage them to break into homes, including homes of innocent people who have never experienced such situations. I've enforced the securing of attractants in two different arenas, and initially approached with education and warnings... Unfortunately, some folks don't head the warnings and turn an ear to education... Encouraging bears with attractants in order to get selfies and photos of bears causes property damage to others and state wildlife agencies kill bears that enter homes... And that includes Moms, leaving orphaned cubs.

Location generalized and obscured to protect the innocent.

description: Second bear within maybe 10 minutes.  This one waddled into the road oblivious to me walking down and in the same direction.  I got his attention with a quiet whistle, and as soon as he saw me, sprinted into the thick riparian

The boldest wild bear I think I've encountered.  Most bolt, but this youngster just waited for me to pass and then went back in the direction it had been heading.  We basically had a mini-traffic jam crossing the creek in the same spot.  

Ten minutes later, another bear waddled out of the woods and didn't see me a little further down the road, and as soon as I got his attention with a whistle, he sprinted off like I typically see.

description:
A rare kind of bear observation for many... Black Bears mating. It was difficult getting photos of other behavior, as they were a "busy" couple. Hopefully these photos are respectful enough to share the rare observation.

Photos 2 - 8 in order, 9th shows the sizes of both bears... The female was about 200 lbs. and the very large male was 3X her size, around 600 lbs. Last photo was the parting pic as I departed quietly and peacefully.

Saw this couple playing on a previous evening among 5 different bears on this mountain slope and 3 others on another slope, (most were foraging)... Decided to hike up to get better photos.

On the edge of last year's Tamarack Fire, where it burned into an area already burned about 7 years ago.

Location generalized and obscured to help keep these bears safe.

Beautiful Mom and a glimpse of her single cub of the year (may add more photos later).

Been watching Mom and her youngster for a few weeks. Most of the time her cub is well hidden. Photos generally in order, and you can see Mom napping close by, and I spent a few hours in their presence. One photo, a bit blurred, shows Mom sitting up and feeding her youngster. I quietly and peacefully walked off.

Location generalized and obscured for their safety.

description:
Saw this beautiful light colored female Black Bear, a bear who is one of the established locals (and knows my scent and presence are not a threat), on the last leg of a very long hike... to visit some places now under lock and key due to last year's Tamarack Fire.

I was about out of water and decided to take a shortcut down a seldom travelled drainage. Took a few photos of shrubs regenerating, then saw her... She was slowly making her way up the burned, dry, and shadeless drainage. Twice she stopped to rest and cool down...
Yes, fire is a natural process, I've worked as a fire rehab specialist, Federal Inspector of contractors resending burns, and a few stints as a Wildland Firefighter... Wildfires are more numerous, intense and larger (on average) as each year passes... Look at this bear struggling with the heat in a huge area that no longer has needed shade or ample food sources through spring, summer, and fall. I documented some of the major foods they were seeking this spring into early summer... Quite a change from what has easily sustained them in the past - before this huge fire and the neighboring even larger Caldor Fire (also last year). The reemerging shrubs are not in a mature fruit producing stage and many usual forbs are lacking or nonexistent. Pine seed/nut production is very low and spotty in trees half-scorched or are in isolated unburned islands...

It's very hard times for bears of this area, very limited foods are now wilted by the above average (constant trend) heat of summer, and insects in snags and downed logs (most burned), and under rocks, are all gone or barely present. Small unburned islands and the fires' edges are extremely important now. Keep in mind that established territories, both seasonal and year long are severely changed and available foods are sought by concentrations of bears.

Things are different in the mountains and elsewhere, and we play the biggest role in these changes.

description:
Another beautiful Black Bear seen this year... while on a monumental late afternoon/evening bear hike on July 9, 2022, to places few humans get to, in steep rugged country of the Eastern Sierra. This bear, whose body characteristics aren't exactly definitive, I'm going with... She, was foraging in an area burned by the Tamarack Fire of last year. I've been documenting the foods bears have been relying on in the huge burn zone, and hope to share those observations down the road... Foods she also sought out in the changed landscape, eventually within 20' of me.

She does have a collar and ear tags, number not revealed here. I'm a strong proponent of learning about bears, their population numbers and dynamics, activity patterns, movements, habitat use and much more including their behavior through observations, their tracks, trails, other sign like beds, scat, marking/scratch trees, straddle trees, wallows, and more, and hair collected from bear sign for DNA (scat too)... There's so much to learn without having to trap, drug, and collar and handle bears... All of which is a bit traumatic for an animal used to being wild and free, and never restrained.

Back to this year's big change in foraging, please see my previous observation for more about the increase of wildfires and their intensity, and their effect on seasonal bear foods and our role in this delima. The fire related food this bear and other bears were foraging for this spring have long since wilted in the now usual above average heat of summer. Traditional foods are scarce to nonexistent.

This was bear number 1 of 4 seen this particular evening, and may share bears number 3 & 4 later.

Last photo is actually one of the first photos, before I made my way up to her. Photos shared are highlights of the over an hour observation. Close up video of her foraging right next to me on Instagram... same username there too.

Location generalized and obscured for the bear's safety and peace.
I saw 2 cubs and a mother climbing up my landlords plum tree.

description: tracks
tracks in sand

No, this is not Big Foot or Sasquatch.  If you look carefully (as if it was 2:25 a.m. in the morning), you'll see the beady eyes of this resting 200-lb Black Bear.  Long story short:  I was the only camper in Leavis Flat Campground on this particular night.  I noticed that the many trash cans--full from weekend visitors--were regular old cans, not bear-proof.  A red flag should have gone off at that point.  At 12:30 a.m., I was awakened by the crashing sounds of a set of trash cans about 20 yards from my car where I was ~ sleeping.  This bear had just overturned that last of the cans in the campground.  The groceries in my car might have been its next target.  I scared it off with some loud yelling and horn honking but it apparently didn't move far.  Being the only camper in the small campground, I decided to take charge and reclaim the campground.  So from 12:30 a.m. to about 3:30 a.m., I would turn on my car and cruise slowly through the campground with my Q-beam, occasionally honking my horn...just in case.  I was unnerved to find the bear returning at least three more times.  Then I caught this glimpse of the bear just resting in some plants across a small creek, about 40 yards from me.  It was just waiting for me to go back to sleep, I suppose.  I was *it's noisy neighbor*.
Well, after more yelling, light shining, and horn honking, the bear finally ambled off into the darkness.  Needless to say, I did not sleep much the rest of the night.  So I'm a little sleep-deprived as I upload these images now (from a safe distance, in a hotel in Kingman, AZ).

As an aside, there were hunters in the area, though bears are protected in the National Forest (or so I am told).  The hunters were off on a trail "behind" us by a 1/4 mile or so heading towards the opposite side of the mountain.
